nges in their quest to have children. Despite current wider social acceptance of single people and same sex couples becoming parents, many of these challenges continue. In Romancing the Sperm, Diane Tober explores the intersections between sperm donation and the broader social and political environment in which "modern families" are created and regulated. Through tangible and intimate stories, this book provides a captivating read for anyone interested in family and kinship, genetics and eugenics, and how ever-expanding assisted reproductive technologies continue to redefine what it means to be human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArtificial inseminationxSocial aspects. 0aFamilies. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxSocial aspects. 0aSingle mothers. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afamily, sperm donor, women, lesbian, LGBTQ, heterosexual, homosexual, couples, marriage, relationship, alternative, children, health policy, reproductive health, sperm bank, mother, motherhood, donor, insemination, modern, technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813590820zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813590820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813590820.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK